headline.main: FRANCE.; The Patrie and the Emperor--The Council of State and the Legislative Body--Cruelty to Amimals--Dramatic--Works of Living Artists--Health of the Empress.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Patrie is beginning again with its pretty stories about the Emperor. The other day he was walking in the enclosed gardens of the Tuileries, with his arms folded behind him, and endeavoring to look as much like his uncle as possible, when he observed a municipal guard. This functionary was on duty at a point where unusual circumspection was necessary.

docs.lead_paragraph: REPORT OF DEATHS.--The Health Officer re ports 43 deaths for the week ending May 28, from the following diseases: Cholera infantum. congestion of lungs, convulsions, dropsy in abdomen, ecrema, hemorrhage of uterine, inflammation of brain, inflammation of stomach, parturition, premature birth, scrofula--one each. Casualty, croup, heart disease, whooping cough, small pox--two each. Drowned and stillborn, three each; inflammation of the lungs, 4; consumption, II. Males 26; Females 17. Adults, 25; Children 18. Total 43.

docs.lead_paragraph: From the London Times. It will he remembered that a few weeks back we had occasion to lay before our readers some communications which we had received with regard to the system followed in the large West-end dressmaking houses. In a letter, which will be found in another portion of our columns this day, it will be seen that the oppressive arrangements complained of are not confined to the west end of the town.

docs.lead_paragraph: This day is coming to be more universally observed than almost any other of our holidays. And this is strange, too; for it is contrary to the spirit of our Christian institutions, contrary to good manners, and contrary to the moneyed interests of the people.
